 term of copyrights become law in the interim, [[Dumbo (1941 film)|Disney's Dumbo (1941)]] will enter the public domain, not only that, [[1941 in literature|Books]], [[1941 in film|other films]], and other works published in 1941 will enter the public domain.\n* [[March 17]] &ndash; Transit of Venus from Uranus\n* [[May 7]] &ndash; [[penumbral lunar eclipse|penumbral]] [[May 2031 lunar eclipse|lunar eclipse]]<ref name=\"NASA Lunar\">{{cite web|url=https://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/LEcat5/LE2001-2100.html|title=Lunar Eclipses: 2001 to 2100|first1=Fred|last1=Espenak|first2=Jean|last2=Meeus|publisher=NASA|date=May 23, 2011|accessdate=August 15, 2017|website=NASA Eclipse Web Site}}</ref>\n* [[May 21]] &ndash; [[annular solar eclipse|annular]] [[Solar eclipse of May 21, 2031|solar eclipse]]<ref name=\"NASA Solar\">{{cite web|url=https://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEdecade/SEdecade2031.html|title=Solar Eclipses: 2031 - 2040|first=Fred|last=Espenak|publisher=NASA|website=NASA Eclipse Web Site|accessdate=August 15, 2017|date=December 9, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[June 5]] &ndash; [[penumbral lunar eclipse|penumbral]] [[June 2031 lunar eclipse|lunar eclipse]]<ref name=\"NASA Lunar\"/>\n* [[October 29]] &ndash; Transit of Venus from Uranus\n* [[October 30]] &ndash; [[penumbral lunar eclipse|penumbral]] [[October 2031 lunar eclipse|lunar eclipse]]<ref name=\"NASA Lunar\"/>\n* [[November 14]] &ndash; [[hybrid solar eclipse|hybrid]] [[Solar eclipse of November 14, 2031|solar eclipse]]<ref name=\"NASA Solar\"/>\n* [[December 17]] &ndash; Transit of Earth from Uranus\n* [[Advanced Telescope for High Energy Astrophysics|ATHENA]] (Advanced Telescope for High Energy Astrophysics), an [[X-ray]] observatory is planned to launch this year.\n\n== In fiction ==\n{{See|21st century in fiction}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2031}}\n[[Category:2031| ]]\n", "name_user": "MightyArms", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2031"}
{"title_page": "Up\u0101li", "text_new": "{{short description|One of Gautama Buddha's main disciples, foremost in monastic discipline}}\n{{good article}}\n{{for|the 18th Century founder of the [[Siyam Nikaya]]|Upali Thera}}\n{{Infobox religious biography\n|background = #FFD068 |\n|name = Up\u0101li\n|image = File:Bodh Gaya - Buddha Statue - Upali (9227722130).jpg\n|caption = Up\u0101li, [[Bodh Gaya]], India\n|other_names = 'repository of the discipline' ({{lang-pi|Vinaye agganikkhitto|italic=yes}}; 'foremost in discipline' ({{lang-pi|Vinaya-p\u0101mokkha|italic=yes}})\n|religion = Buddhism\n|school = all, but mostly discussed in [[P\u0101li]] Buddhism\n|lineage = ''Vinayadhara''\n|honorific-prefix = [[thero|Elder]]\n|teacher = The [[Buddha]], Kappitaka\n|successor = D\u0101saka\n|students = ''Sattarasavaggiy\u0101'', D\u0101saka\n|known_for = Expertise in [[vinaya|monastic discipline]], reviewed monastic discipline during the [[First Buddhist Council|First Council]]\n| initiation_place = [[Malla (India)|Anupiy\u0101]]\n| initiator        = the Buddha\n|period = [[Early Buddhism]]\n}}\n\n'''Up\u0101li''' ([[Sanskrit]] and [[P\u0101li]]) was a monk, one of the [[The ten principal disciples|ten chief disciples]] of the [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]]{{sfn |Ray |1994 |pp=205\u2013206 note 2a\u2013d}} and according to [[Early Buddhist Texts|early Buddhist texts]], the person in charge of the reciting and reviewing of [[vinaya|monastic discipline]] ([[P\u0101li]] and {{lang-sa|vinaya|italic=yes}}) on the [[First Buddhist Council]]. Up\u0101li was born a low-caste barber. He met the Buddha when still a child, and later, when the [[Shakya|Sakya]] princes received [[pabbajja|ordination]], he did so as well. He was, in fact, ordained before the princes, putting humility before caste. Having been ordained, Up\u0101li learnt both Buddhist doctrine ({{lang-pi|Dhamma|italic=yes}}; {{lang-sa|Dharma|italic=yes}}) and ''vinaya''. His [[Upadhyay#In_Buddhism|preceptor]] was Kappitaka. Up\u0101li became known for his mastery and strictness of ''vinaya'', and was consulted often about ''vinaya'' matters. A notable case he decided about was that of the monk Ajjuka, who was accused of partisanship in a conflict about real estate. During the First Council, Up\u0101li received the important role of reciting the ''vinaya'', for which he is mostly known.\n\nScholars have analyzed Up\u0101li's role and that of other disciples in the early texts, and it has been suggested that his role in the texts was emphasized during a period of compiling that stressed monastic discipline, during which [[Mahakassapa|Mah\u0101kassapa]] ({{lang-sa|Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa}}) and Up\u0101li became the most important disciples. Later, Up\u0101li and his pupils became known as ''vinayadharas'' ([[P\u0101li]]; 'custodians of the vinaya'), who preserved the monastic discipline after the Buddha's ''[[parinirvana|parinibb\u0101na]]'' ({{lang-sa|parinirv\u0101\u1e47a|italic=yes}}; passing into final Nirvana). This lineage became an important part of the identity of [[Ceylon|Ceylonese]] and Burmese Buddhism. In China, the 7th-century Vinaya school referred to Up\u0101li as their patriarch, and it was believed that one of their founders was a reincarnation of him. The technical conversations about ''vinaya'' between the Buddha and Up\u0101li were recorded in the P\u0101li and [[Sarvastivada|Sarv\u0101stiv\u0101da]] traditions, and have been suggested as an important subject of study for modern-day ethics in [[American Buddhism]].\n\n== Accounts ==\nUp\u0101li the barber\u2019s personality is not depicted extensively in the texts, as the texts mostly emphasize his stereotypical qualities as an expert in monastic discipline, especially so in the [[P\u0101li]] texts.{{sfn |Freedman |1977 |pp=67, 231}}\n\n=== Early life ===\nAccording to the texts, Up\u0101li was therefore a barber, a despised profession in ancient India.{{sfn |Rhys Davids |1899 |p=102}}{{sfn |Gombrich |1995 |p=357}} He was from an [[Vaishya|artisan caste]] family in service to the [[Shakya|Sakya]] princes in [[Kapilavatthu]] ({{lang-sa|\u015aakya; Kapilavastu}}) and, according to the ''[[Mah\u0101vastu]]'', to the Buddha. Up\u0101li's mother had once introduced Up\u0101li to the Buddha.{{sfn |Mrozik |2004}} The ''Mah\u0101vastu'', [[Dharmaguptaka]] and Chinese texts relate that as a child, Up\u0101li shaved the hair of the Buddha. Unlike adults, he had no fear of approaching the Buddha. Once, as he was guided by the Buddha during the shaving, he attained [[jhana|advanced states of meditation]]. Buddhologist [[Andr\u00e9 Bareau]] argues that this story is ancient, because it precedes the tradition of art depictions of the Buddha with curly hair, and the glorification of Up\u0101li as an adult.{{sfn |Bareau |1962 |p=262}}\n\nAccording to the Mah\u0101vastu, the P\u0101li [[Cullavagga]] and the texts of discipline of the [[M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101da]] order, when the princes left home to become monks, Up\u0101li followed them. Since the princes handed Up\u0101li all their possessions, including jewelry, he figured that returning to Kapilavatthu with these possessions might cause him to be accused of having killed the princes for theft. Up\u0101li therefore decided to become ordained with them. They were ordained by the Buddha at the [[Malla (India)|Anupiy\u0101 grove]].{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=Up\u0101li}}. For the texts of traditions apart from P\u0101li, see {{harvtxt |Freedman |1977 |p=97}}.}} Several variations on the story of Up\u0101li's ordination exist, but all of them emphasize that his status in the ''sa\u1e45gha'' ({{lang-sa|sa\u1e43gha|italic=yes}}; monastic community) was independent of his caste origin. In the P\u0101li version, the princes, including [[Anuruddha]] ({{lang-sa|Aniruddha}}), voluntarily allowed Up\u0101li to ordain before them in order to give him seniority in order of ordination and abandon their own attachment to caste and social status.{{sfn |Freedman |1977 |p=117}}[[File:Kapilavastu.jpg|thumb|Remains at [[Tilaurakot]], one of the two sites that may have been Kapilavatthu |alt=Ruins of walled buildings]] In the Tibetan M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101da version of the story, co-disciple [[Sariputra|S\u0101riputta]] ({{lang-sa|\u015a\u0101riputra}}) persuaded Up\u0101li to become ordained when he hesitated because of being low caste, but in the ''Mah\u0101vastu'', it was Up\u0101li's own initiative.{{sfn |Freedman |1977 |p=117}}{{sfn |Mrozik |2004}} The ''Mah\u0101vastu'' continues that after all the monks had been ordained, the Buddha requested that the former princes bow for their former barber, which led to consternation among the witnessing king [[Bimbisara|Bimbis\u0101ra]] and advisers, who also bowed for Up\u0101li following their example.{{sfn |Bareau |1988 |p=76}} It became widely known that the Sakyans had their barber ordained before them to humble their pride,{{sfn |Freedman |1977 |p=116}} as the Buddha related a ''[[Jataka|J\u0101taka]]'' tale that the king and advisers had bowed for Up\u0101li in a previous life, too.{{sfn |Bareau |1988 |p=76}}{{sfn |Rahula |1978 |p=10}}\n\nIndologist [[T.W. Rhys Davids]] noted that Up\u0101li was the \"striking proof of the reality of the effect produced by Gautama's disregard of the supposed importance of caste\".{{sfn |Rhys Davids |1903 |p=69}} Historian {{ill|H.W. Schumann|de}} also raises Up\u0101li as an example of the general rule that \"in no case did ... humble origins prevent a monk from becoming prominent in the [[sangha|Order]]\".{{sfn |Schumann |2004 |p=166}} Religion scholar Jeffrey Samuels points out, though, that the majority of Buddhist monks and [[bhikkhuni|nuns]], as drawn from several analyses of Buddhist texts, were from higher castes, with a minority of six percent like Up\u0101li being exception to the rule.{{sfn |Samuels |2007 |p=123}} Historian Sangh Sen Singh argues that Up\u0101li could have been the leader of the ''sa\u1e45gha'' after the Buddha's ''[[parinibb\u0101na]]'' instead of [[Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa|Mah\u0101kassapa]] ({{lang-sa|parinirv\u0101\u1e47a|italic=yes}}, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa). But the fact that he was from a low caste effectively prevented this, as many of the Buddhist devotees at the time might have objected to his leadership position.{{sfn |Singh |1973 |pp=131\u2013132}}\n\n=== Monastic life ===\nUp\u0101li had a dwelling place in [[Vaishali (ancient city)|Ves\u0101li]] ({{lang-sa|Vai\u015b\u0101li}}), called V\u0101lik\u0101r\u0101ma.<!--Calikarama-->{{sfn |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=Up\u0101li; V\u0101lik\u0101r\u0101ma}}{{sfn |Geiger |1912 |p=35}} He once asked the Buddha for leave to withdraw in the forest and lead a life in solitude. The Buddha refused, however, and told him that such a life was not for everyone.<!--Upali Sutta--> P\u0101li scholar [[Gunapala Piyasena Malalasekera|Gunapala Malalasekera]] argued that the Buddha wanted Up\u0101li to learn both meditation and Buddhist doctrine, and a life in the forest would have provided him with only the former. The texts state that the Buddha himself taught the ''[[vinaya]]'' (monastic discipline) to Up\u0101li.<!--Upali-->{{sfn |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=Up\u0101li; Up\u0101li Sutta (3)}} Up\u0101li later attained the state of an [[arhat|enlightened disciple]].{{sfn |Mrozik |2004}}{{sfn |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=Up\u0101li}}\n\nAccording to the Mah\u0101vastu, the [[Upadhyay#In Buddhism|preceptor]] who completed the process of Up\u0101li's [[upasampada|acceptance]] in the ''sa\u1e45gha'' was a monk called Kappitaka.{{sfn |Freedman |1977 |p=58}}{{refn |group=note |Philosopher Michael Freedman argues that the office of preceptor may have only been developed after the Buddha's ''parinibb\u0101na'', although he admits the texts contradict each other with regard to Up\u0101li's acceptance.{{sfn |Freedman |1977 |pp=57 n.60, 97\u201398}}}} There is one story told about Up\u0101li and his preceptor. Kappitaka was in the habit of living in cemeteries. In one cemetery near Ves\u0101li he had a [[monastic cell]]. One day, a couple of nuns built a small monument there in honor of their teacher, also a nun, and made much noise in the process. Disturbed by the nuns, Kappitaka destroyed the monument, which greatly angered the nuns. Later, in an attempt to kill Kappitaka, they destroyed his cell in return. But Kappitaka was warned by Up\u0101li in advance and he had already fled elsewhere.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=Kappitaka Thera}} The next day, Up\u0101li was verbally abused by the nuns for having informed his teacher.{{sfn |Dhammadinna |2016 |pp=45\u201346}}\n\n=== Role in monastic discipline ===\n[[File:Upali (Ubari), from the series \u201cTwo Bodhisattva and Ten Great Disciples of Sakyamuni\u201d.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|Up\u0101li, woodblock print by [[Munakata Shik\u014d]], originally from 1939|left|alt=Monk in black robes looking at the sky with hands held up]]\n\nIn the literature of every Buddhist school, Up\u0101li is depicted as an expert in ''vinaya'' and the ''[[p\u0101\u1e6dimokkha]]'' ({{lang-sa|pratimok\u1e63a|italic=yes}}; monastic code),{{sfn |Mrozik |2004}} for which the Buddha declared him [[\u015ar\u0101vaka#Foremost disciples|foremost]] among those who remember the vinaya ({{lang-pi|Vinaya-p\u0101mokkha|italic=yes}}; {{lang-sa|Vinayapramukkha|italic=yes}}).{{sfn |Sarao |2004 |p=878}}{{sfn |Robinson |Johnson |1997 |p=45}} He was therefore dubbed the 'repository of the discipline' ({{lang-pi|Vinaye agganikkhitto|italic=yes}}).{{sfn |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=Up\u0101li}} In some schools, he is also seen as an expert in the [[Bodhisattva Precepts|precepts]] of a ''[[bodhisattva|bodhisatta]]'' ({{lang-sa|bodhisattva|italic=yes}}; Buddha-to-be).{{sfn |Mrozik |2004}} 5th-century ommentator [[Buddhaghosa]] stated that Up\u0101li drew up instructions and explanatory notes for monks dealing with disciplinary matters.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=Up\u0101li}}\n\nUp\u0101li was also known for his strictness in practicing the discipline.{{sfn |Baroni |2002 |p=365}} Monks considered it a privilege to study the ''vinaya'' under him.{{sfn |Sarao |2003 |p=4}} At times, monks who felt repentance and wanted to improve themselves, sought his advice.<!--Raman\u012byavih\u0101r\u012b Thera--> In other cases, Up\u0101li was consulted in making decisions considering alleged offenses of monastic discipline. For example, one newly ordained nun was found pregnant, and was judged by the monk [[Devadatta]] as unfit to be a nun. However, the Buddha had Up\u0101li do a second investigation, during which Up\u0101li called upon the help of the laywoman [[Visakha|Visakh\u0101]] and several other laypeople. Eventually, Up\u0101li concluded the nun had conceived the child by her husband before her ordination as a nun, and therefore was innocent. The Buddha later praised Up\u0101li for his careful consideration of this matter.<!--Kum\u0101ra-Kassapa-->{{sfn |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=Kum\u0101ra-Kassapa; Raman\u012byavih\u0101r\u012b Thera}}\n\nOther notable cases about which Up\u0101li decided are that of the monks Bharukaccha and Ajjuka. Bharukaccha consulted Up\u0101li whether dreaming about having sex with a woman amounted to an offense that required disrobing, and Up\u0101li judged it did not.<!--Bharukaccha--> As for the monk Ajjuka, he had decided about a dispute about real estate.<!--Ajjuka-->{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=Ajjuka; Bharukaccha}}. For the other laypeople, see {{harvtxt |Churn Law |2000 |p=464}}.}} In this  case, a rich householder was in doubt as to who he should will his inheritance to, his pious nephew or his own son. He asked Ajjuka to invite for an audience the person who had the most faith of the two{{em dash}}Ajjuka invited the nephew. Angry about the decision, the son accused Ajjuka of partisanship and went to see the monk [[\u0100nanda]]. \u0100nanda disagreed with Ajjuka's decision, judging the son the more rightful heir, and causing the son to feel justified in accusing Ajjuka of not being a \"true monk\". When Up\u0101li got involved, however, he judged in favor of Ajjuka. He pointed out to \u0100nanda that the act of inviting a layperson did not break monastic discipline.{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Huxley |2010 |p=278}}. {{harvtxt |Freedman |1977 |pp=30\u201332}} mentions faith, the son seeing \u0100nanda, and the accusation of false monkhood.}} Eventually, \u0100nanda agreed with Up\u0101li, and Up\u0101li was able to settle the issue.{{sfn |Freedman |1977 |p=32}}{{sfn |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=Ajjuka}} Here, too, the Buddha praised Up\u0101li for his handling of the case.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1961}} Law scholar [[Andrew Huxley (law scholar)|Andrew Huxley]] noted that Up\u0101li's judgment of this case allowed monks to engage on an ethical level with the world, whereas \u0100nanda's judgment did not.{{sfn |Huxley |2010 |p=278}}\n\n=== First Council and death ===\n[[File:Nava Jetavana Temple - Shravasti - 013 First Council at Rajagaha (9241729223).jpg|The First Council. Mural painting in the Nava Jetavana temple, Jetavana Park, [[Uttar Pradesh]], India, late 20th century |thumb |alt=Mural painting with many monks sitting in a cave, one of them seated on a bench]]\nAccording to the [[Va\u1e43sa#Buddhism|chronicles]], Up\u0101li had been ordained (or, was aged{{sfn |Prebish |2008 |p=9}}) forty-four years at the time of the [[First Buddhist Council]].{{sfn |Geiger |1912 |p=xlviii}} At the council, Up\u0101li was asked to recite the ''vinaya'' of monks and nuns, including the ''p\u0101\u1e6dimokkha'',{{refn |For the ''p\u0101\u1e6dimokkha'', see {{harvtxt |Norman |1983 |pp=7\u201312}}. For the ''vinaya'' of both monks and nuns, see {{harvtxt |Oldenberg |1899 |pp=617\u2013618}} and {{harvtxt |Norman |1983 |p=18}}.}}, and the [[vinaya-pitaka|Vinayapi\u1e6daka]] (collection of texts on monastic discipline) was compiled based thereon.{{sfn |Eliade |1982 |pp=210\u2013211}} Specifically, Up\u0101li was asked about each rule issued by the Buddha as to what it was about, where it was issued, with regard to whom, the formulation of the rule itself, derived secondary rules, and the conditions under which the rule was broken.{{sfn |Thomas |1951 |p=28}} According to the [[Mahasamghika|Mah\u0101sa\u1e43ghika]] account of the First Council, Up\u0101li was the one who charged \u0100nanda, the former attendant of the Buddha, with several offenses of wrongdoing.{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Analayo |2010 |p=17 note 52}}. For the Mah\u0101sa\u1e43ghika, see {{harvtxt |Analayo |2016 |p=160}}.}}\n\nUp\u0101li had a number of pupils, who were called the ''sattarasavaggiy\u0101''.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=R\u0101jagaha}} Up\u0101li and his pupils were entrusted with the [[Bh\u0101\u1e47aka|safekeeping and reciting]] of this collection of monastic discipline.{{sfn |Norman |2005 |p=37}} Sixteen years after the Buddha's [[parinirvana|passing away]], Up\u0101li ordained a pupil called D\u0101saka, who would become his successor with regard to expertise in monastic discipline. According to the late P\u0101li ''[[Dipavamsa|D\u012bpava\u1e43sa]]'', Up\u0101li died at the age of seventy-four, if this age is interpreted as life-span, not years of ordination.{{sfn |Prebish |2008 |p=9}}\n\n=== Previous lives ===\n<!--disabled[[File:Indian relief from Amaravati, Guntur. Preserved in Guimet Museum.jpg|Wheel-turning king ({{lang-pi|cakkavatti|italic=yes}}; {{lang-sa|cakravartin|italic=yes}}), {{circa}} 1st century CE, India|thumb |alt=Relief of figure raising arm, surrounded by wheel, a horse and three other figures, two male, one female |upright=.6]]-->\nIn some Buddhist texts, an explanation is offered why a low-caste born monk would have such a central role in developing monastic law. The question that might have been raised is whether issuing laws would not normally be associated with kings. The ''[[Apadana|Apad\u0101na]]'' explains this by relating that Up\u0101li had been an all-powerful [[cakravartin|wheel-turning king]] for thousand previous lives, and a king of the [[deva (Buddhism)|deities]] in another thousand lives.{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Huxley |1996 |p=126 note 27}} and {{harvtxt |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=Up\u0101li}}. Huxley mentions the question raised.}} Before that, the texts say he was born during the age of [[Padumuttara Buddha]] and met one of that [[Buddha (title)|Buddha]]'s disciples who was foremost in monastic discipline. Up\u0101li aspired to be like him, and pursued it through doing [[merit (Buddhism)|merits]].{{sfn |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=Up\u0101li}}{{sfn |Cutler |1997 |p=66}}\n\nDespite Up\u0101li's previous lives as a king, he was born as a low caste barber in the time of [[Gotama Buddha]]. This is also explained in an ''Apad\u0101na'' story: in a previous life, Up\u0101li insulted a ''[[paccekabuddha]]'' ({{lang-sa|pratyekabuddha|italic=yes}}; a type of Buddha). The evil [[karma in Buddhism|karma]] brought about low birth.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=Up\u0101li}}{{sfn |Cutler |1997 |p=66}}\n\n== Legacy ==\nUp\u0101li was the focus of worship in ancient and medieval India and was regarded as the \"patron saint\" of monks who specialize in the ''vinaya''.{{sfn |Mrozik |2004}}{{sfn |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=Hsuan Tsang}} He is one of the [[eight enlightened disciples]], and is honored in Burmese ceremonies.{{sfn |Mrozik |2004}}{{sfn|Strong |1992 |p=240}}\n\n=== Schools and lineages ===\n[[File:Mah\u0101vih\u0101ra on 1890 map of Anuradhapura.svg|1890 map showing the historical location of the Mah\u0101vih\u0101ra, drawn by a British civil servant |alt=Map of Anurudhapura, the city that included the Mahvihara |thumb]]\nSeveral scholars have contended that the prominence of certain of the Buddha's disciples in the early texts is indicative of the preference of the compilers. Buddhologist [[Jean Przyluski]] argued that Up\u0101li's prominence in the P\u0101li texts is indicative of the preference of the [[Sthavira]]v\u0101dins for ''vinaya'' above [[sutra|discourse]], whereas the prominence of \u0100nanda in the M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101da texts is indicative of their preference for discourse above ''vinaya''.{{sfn |Freedman |1977 |pp=13, 464\u2013465}}{{sfn |Przyluski |1923 |pp=22\u201323}} This preference of the compilers has also affected how \u0100nanda addresses Up\u0101li.<!--34-35--> In many of the early discourses Up\u0101li has little to no role,<!--88--> and he is not mentioned among many early lists of significant disciples.<!--89--> He is, however, frequently mentioned in lists in the ''Vinaya-pi\u1e6daka'', which only proves the point. Up\u0101li seems to obtain a much more significant role with the end of the Buddha's life.<!--110-->{{sfn |Freedman |1977 |pp=34\u201335, 88\u201389, 110}} Przyluski's theory, which was further developed by Buddhologist Andr\u00e9 Migot, regarded [[Mahakassapa|Mah\u0101kassapa]] ({{lang-sa|Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa}}), Up\u0101li and [[Anuruddha]] ({{lang-sa|Aniruddha}}) as part of the second period in the compiling of the early texts (4th to early 3rd century BCE) that emphasized [[\u015b\u012bla|moral discipline]], associated with these disciples, as well as the city of [[Vesali|Ves\u0101l\u012b]] ({{lang-sa|Vai\u015bal\u012b}}).{{refn |group=note |Although Przyluski connected this with the city of [[Kosambi|Kosamb\u012b]] ({{lang-sa|Kau\u015bamb\u012b}}) instead.{{sfn |Przyluski |1923 |p=184}}}} In this period, these disciples' roles and stories were emphasized and embellished more than other disciples.{{sfn |Migot |1954 |pp=540\u2013541}} These differences in schools gradually developed and became stereotyped over time.{{sfn |Dutt |1925 |pp=206\u2013207}}\n\nUp\u0101li's successors formed a [[Lineage (Buddhism)|lineage]] called the ''vinayadharas'', or the 'custodians of the vinaya'.{{sfn |Sarao |2003 |p=3}}{{sfn |Prebish |2008 |p=2}} ''Vinayadharas'' were monks who in [[early Buddhist Texts|early Buddhist texts]] were particularly known for their mastery and strictness with regard to the ''vinaya''. In 4th<!--2-->\u20135th-century<!--3--> [[Ceylon]], they then came to be associated with a lineage of such masters,<!--2--> because of the influence of Buddhaghosa, who established Up\u0101li and the other ''vinayadharas'' as an important characteristic<!--3--> of the [[Anuradhapura Maha Viharaya|Mah\u0101vih\u0101ra]] tradition.<!--12--> This concept of a ''vinayadhara'' lineage also affected Burma, and led to a belief that only those ordained in the proper lineage could become ''vinayadharas''.<!--3--> Gradually, the ''vinayadhara'' came to be seen a sign of superior tradition, as the lineage was integrated with local history.<!--12--> Even later, the ''vinayadhara'' became a formal position<!--14--> of judge and arbitrator in problems of ''vinaya''.<!--4-->{{sfn |Frasch |1996 |pp=2\u20134, 12, 14}}\n\nUp\u0101li's lineage has gained scholarly attention because of their way of timekeeping, known by modern scholars as the \"dotted record\". Chinese sources say that Up\u0101li and his successors had a custom to insert a dot in a manuscript marking each year after the First Council. The sources claim that each of successors continued this tradition, up until 489 CE, when the [[Sarv\u0101stiv\u0101da]] scholar [[Sa\u1e43ghabhadra]]  entered the last dot in the manuscript. This tradition has been used by some modern scholars to calculate the [[parinirvana|passing away]] of the Buddha,<!--6--> but has now been debunked as historically unlikely.<!--7--> Still, data pertaining to the ''vinayadharas'' is used to support theories regarding the dating of the Buddha's life and death,<!--6--> such as the one proposed by Indologist [[Richard Gombrich]].<!--8-->{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Prebish |2008 |pp=6\u20138}}. {{harvtxt |Geiger |1912 |p=xlvii}} mentions the term ''para\u1e43par\u0101''.}}\n[[File:Daoxuan (Nara National Museum).jpg|thumb|The Chinese Vinaya school founded by Tao-hs\u00fcan saw themselves as the continuation of Up\u0101li's lineage ([[Important Cultural Properties of Japan|ICP]], [[Nara National Museum]]) |upright=.7]]\nNot only in ancient India did certain lineages identify with Up\u0101li. In 7th-century China, the Vinaya or Nan-shan School was founded by the monks Ku-hsin and [[Tao-hs\u00fcan]], seen as a continuation of Up\u0101li's lineage. The school emphasized restoring and propagating the ''vinaya'' and became popular in the Pa Hwa Hills of [[Nanking]]. It developed a standard for teaching the ''vinaya''. The monks would wear black and emphasized protecting oneself against error. It was believed at the time that Ku-hsin was a reincarnation of Up\u0101li.{{refn |For Ku-hsin, the Pa Hwa Hills, the standard and the reincarnation, see {{harvtxt |Hsiang-Kuang |1956 |p=207}}. For Tao-hs\u00fcan and the monks, see {{harvtxt |Bapat |1956 |pp=126\u2013127}}.}}\n\n=== Texts ===\nIn the P\u0101li tradition, numerous discourses show the Buddha and Up\u0101li discussing matters of monastic discipline, including the legality of decision-making and assemblies, and the system of giving warnings and probation. Much of this is found in the ''[[Pariv\u0101ra]]'', a late ''vinaya'' text.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=Up\u0101li}} Bareau has suggested the conversation between the Buddha and Up\u0101li about schisms was the origin of the traditions about this subject in the ''Vinayapi\u1e6daka''.{{sfn |Ray |1994 |p=169}} In the ''vinaya'' texts of the Sarvastiv\u0101da tradition, the ''Uttragrantha''{{sfn |Thomas |1951 |p=268}} and the 5th-century [[Mah\u0101y\u0101na]]-inspired ''Upalipariprccha''{{refn |For the Mah\u0101y\u0101na influence, see {{harvtxt |Prebish |2010 |p=305}} For the time period, see {{harvtxt |Agostini |2004 |p=80 n.42}}.}}  feature similar to almost the same questions as the P\u0101li ''P\u0101riv\u0101ra'',{{sfn |Norman |1983 |p=29}} although the suggestion that the latter originates from a no longer extant P\u0101li text has not been proven.{{sfn |Heirman |2004 |p=377}} The [[Turkistan]] Sanskrit version of the ''Uttragrantha'', on the other hand, does not match the P\u0101li at all.{{sfn |Norman |1983 |p=29}} With regard to these lists of questions, it is unknown which of these questions are from Up\u0101li, and which were attributed to him because of his reputation.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=Up\u0101li}} Apart from these technical discussions, there is also a teaching given by Up\u0101li referred to in the P\u0101li ''[[Milindapanha|Milindapa\u00f1h\u0101]]''.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=Up\u0101li}} Religion scholar Charles Prebish has named the ''Upalipariprccha'' as one of twenty-two texts worthy of study and practice, in order to develop an [[american Buddhism|American Buddhist]] ethics.{{sfn |Prebish |2000 |pp=56\u201357 |ps=: \"... texts worthy of new consideration would also include those with the richest heritage of ethical underpinnings.\"}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist |group=note}}\n\n== Citations ==\n{{reflist |20em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin |30em}}\n* {{Citation |last=Agostini |first=G. |year=2004 |title=Buddhist Sources on Feticide as Distinct from Homicide |journal=Journal of the International Association of Buddhist Studies |volume=27 |issue=1 |pages=63{{en dash}}95 |url=https://www.academia.edu/2293009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824125105/https://www.academia.edu/2293009/Buddhist_Sources_on_Feticide_as_Distinct_from_Homicide |archive-date=7 March 2020 |url-status=live}}\n* {{Citation |last=Analayo |first=B. |year=2010 |title=Once Again on Bakkula |author-link=Bhikkhu Analayo |journal=The Indian International Journal of Buddhist Studies |volume=11 |pages=1\u201328 |url=https://www.buddhismuskunde.uni-hamburg.de/pdf/5-personen/analayo/once-again-bakkula.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304100839/https://www.buddhismuskunde.uni-hamburg.de/pdf/5-personen/analayo/once-again-bakkula.pdf |archive-date=4 March 2020 |url-status=l